# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: okhttp-java-lib
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] In software engineering, a **connection pool** is a cache of reusable database connections managed by the client or middleware.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] It reduces the overhead of opening and closing connections, improving performance and scalability in database applications.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] SQL databases typically use stateful, binary protocols that maintain session-specific information, such as transaction states and prepared statements, necessitating optimized connection pooling to minimize the overhead of repeatedly establishing connections.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Conversely, many mainstream NoSQL databases, like Azure Cosmos DB and Amazon DynamoDB, utilize stateless, HTTP-based protocols that handle each request independently.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] This architecture often reduces the need for traditional connection pooling, though reusing established connections can still offer performance benefits in high-throughput scenarios by avoiding the overhead of connection creation.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] In database environments, connection limits are typically determined by service tiers or resource configurations.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Azure SQL Database defines connection limits based on the selected tier, while Azure SQL Managed Instance enforces limits based on allocated resources, such as CPU, memory, or vCores.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] When connection pool configurations exceed these limits, issues such as rejected connections, throttling, or degraded performance can occur.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Depending on how database limits are applied, overprovisioned connection pools can create significant resource contention as the server struggles to manage excessive simultaneous connections.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Idle connections may encounter issues due to network conditions, such as NAT timeouts or dropped connections, or database state changes, such as session invalidation or transaction timeouts, potentially triggering reconnection processes that introduce additional overhead and performance penalties.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Over-provisioned pools can overwhelm server resources, causing increased latency and degraded system performance.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Token-based authentication mechanisms, such as Azure AD authentication, may affect connection pooling due to token expiration.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Expired tokens can invalidate connections within the pool, interrupting reuse.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] This behavior is observed in both cloud-based and on-premises database systems that implement modern authentication protocols.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] The efficiency of connection pooling can be influenced by network latency and endpoint configurations.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Public endpoints, commonly used in cloud-hosted databases, often introduce higher latency compared to private or direct connections.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] In environments with dynamic IP addressing, such as those involving cloud-native applications, disruptions in connection reuse may occur if firewall rules are not synchronized with changing IP addresses.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Databases that enforce TLS encryption, including those deployed in cloud and on-premises environments, require alignment between encryption settings and connection configurations.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] For example, the absence of encryption parameters in connection strings can lead to connection failures, rendering the pool ineffective.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Private endpoints and custom DNS configurations can create challenges for connection pooling.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Inconsistent or misconfigured DNS settings may delay or block connection establishment, affecting the performance and efficiency of connection reuse.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] This is particularly notable in environments with hybrid or private cloud setups.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] In modern cloud architectures like AWS, effective connection pooling management is critical for optimizing performance, scalability, and resource utilization.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Improper handling of connections can lead to bottlenecks and operational inefficiencies.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Containerized Environments: Amazon Elastic Container Service (ECS) containers maintain open database connections for their lifecycle.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Without connection pooling mechanisms (e.g., HikariCP, pgbouncer), idle or excessive connections can strain database resources.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Virtual Machine-Based Environments: AWS EC2 instances scale connection demand with the number of instances.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Manual or automated tuning of connection pool parameters is essential to prevent exceeding database limits.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] This ecosystem of tools and services empowers architects to design highly scalable and efficient applications while minimizing connection management overhead.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Azure SQL Database, Azure SQL Managed Instance, and SQL Server on virtual machines rely on client-side connection pooling implemented by libraries such as ADO.NET and JDBC.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] The database engine does not manage pooling, as it is entirely handled at the client level.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] Environmental factors, including service-tier limits in Azure SQL Database and resource constraints in Managed Instance, may indirectly affect pooling performance.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] In Azure Cosmos DB, connection pooling is managed at the SDK level rather than by the database service itself.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] SDKs such as those for .NET, Java, and Python implement connection pooling to reuse HTTP connections to the database endpoint, optimizing resource usage and performance.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] This functionality applies to all Cosmos DB account types, including provisioned throughput and serverless models.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/connection-pool] The stateless, HTTP-based architecture of Cosmos DB facilitates scalable and concurrent operations without the limitations typically associated with traditional connection pooling mechanisms.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/http-client] On the Web, a **user agent** is a software agent responsible for retrieving and facilitating end-user interaction with Web content.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/http-client] This includes all web browsers, such as Google Chrome and Safari, some email clients, standalone download managers like youtube-dl, and other command-line utilities like cURL.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/http-client] The user agent is the client in a client–server system.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/http-client] The HTTP User-Agent header is intended to clearly identify the agent to the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/http-client] However, this header can be omitted or spoofed, so some websites use other detection methods.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Having solved the memory management problem does not relieve the programmer of the burden of handling properly other kinds of resources, like network or database connections, file handles, etc., especially in the presence of exceptions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The syntax of Java is largely influenced by C++ and C.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, which combines the syntax for structured, generic, and object-oriented programming, Java was built almost exclusively as an object-oriented language.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] All code is written inside classes, and every data item is an object, with the exception of the primitive data types, (i.e. integers, floating-point numbers, boolean values, and characters), which are not objects for performance reasons.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Unlike C++, Java does not support operator overloading or multiple inheritance for classes, though multiple inheritance is supported for interfaces.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java uses comments similar to those of C++.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] There are three different styles of comments: a single line style marked with two slashes (`//`), a multiple line style opened with `/*` and closed with `*/`, and the Javadoc commenting style opened with `/**` and closed with `*/`.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The Javadoc style of commenting allows the user to run the Javadoc executable to create documentation for the program and can be read by some integrated development environments (IDEs) such as Eclipse to allow developers to access documentation within the IDE.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java applets were programs embedded in other applications, mainly in web pages displayed in web browsers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The Java applet API was deprecated with the release of Java 9 in 2017.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] JSPs embed Java code in an HTML page by using the special delimiters `<%` and `%>`.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] A JSP is compiled to a Java *servlet*, a Java application in its own right, the first time it is accessed.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] After that, the generated servlet creates the response.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Swing is a graphical user interface library for the Java SE platform.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] It is possible to specify a different look and feel through the pluggable look and feel system of Swing.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Clones of Windows, GTK+, and Motif are supplied by Sun.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Apple also provides an Aqua look and feel for macOS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Where prior implementations of these looks and feels may have been considered lacking, Swing in Java SE 6 addresses this problem by using more native GUI widget drawing routines of the underlying platforms.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] JavaFX is a software platform for creating and delivering desktop applications, as well as rich web applications that can run across a wide variety of devices.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] JavaFX is intended to replace Swing as the standard graphical user interface (GUI) library for Java SE, but since JDK 11 JavaFX has not been in the core JDK and is instead available as a separate module.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] JavaFX has support for desktop computers and web browsers on Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] JavaFX does not have support for native OS look and feels.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] In 2004, generics were added to the Java language, as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Prior to the introduction of generics, each variable declaration had to be of a specific type.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] For container classes, for example, this is a problem because there is no easy way to create a container that accepts only specific types of objects.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Either the container operates on all subtypes of a class or interface, usually `Object`, or a different container class has to be created for each contained class.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Generics allow compile-time type checking without having to create many container classes, each containing almost identical code.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] In addition to enabling more efficient code, certain runtime exceptions are prevented from occurring, by issuing compile-time errors.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] If Java prevented all runtime type errors (`ClassCastException`s) from occurring, it would be type safe.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] In 2016, the type system of Java was proven unsound in that it is possible to use generics to construct classes and methods that allow assignment of an instance of one class to a variable of another unrelated class.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Such code is accepted by the compiler, but fails at run time with a class cast exception.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Criticisms directed at Java include the implementation of generics, speed, the handling of unsigned numbers, the implementation of floating-point arithmetic, and a history of security vulnerabilities in the primary Java VM implementation HotSpot.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Developers have criticized the complexity and verbosity of the Java Persistence API (JPA), a standard part of Java EE.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] This has led to increased adoption of higher-level abstractions like Spring Data JPA, which aims to simplify database operations and reduce boilerplate code.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The growing popularity of such frameworks suggests limitations in the standard JPA implementation's ease-of-use for modern Java development.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The Java Class Library is the standard library, developed to support application development in Java.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] It is controlled by Oracle in cooperation with others through the Java Community Process program.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Companies or individuals participating in this process can influence the design and development of the APIs.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] This process has been a subject of controversy during the 2010s.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Javadoc is a comprehensive documentation system, created by Sun Microsystems.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] It provides developers with an organized system for documenting their code.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Javadoc comments have an extra asterisk at the beginning, i.e. the delimiters are `/**` and `*/`, whereas the normal multi-line comments in Java are delimited by `/*` and `*/`, and single-line comments start with `//`.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle Corporation owns the official implementation of the Java SE platform, due to its acquisition of Sun Microsystems on January 27, 2010.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] This implementation is based on the original implementation of Java by Sun.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The Oracle implementation is available for Windows, macOS, Linux, and Solaris.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Because Java lacks any formal standardization recognized by Ecma International, ISO/IEC, ANSI, or other third-party standards organizations, the Oracle implementation is the de facto standard.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle has also released GraalVM, a high performance Java dynamic compiler and interpreter.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] OpenJDK is another Java SE implementation that is licensed under the GNU GPL.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The implementation started when Sun began releasing the Java source code under the GPL.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] As of Java SE 7, OpenJDK is the official Java reference implementation.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The goal of Java is to make all implementations of Java compatible.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Historically, Sun's trademark license for usage of the Java brand insists that all implementations be *compatible*.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] This resulted in a legal dispute with Microsoft after Sun claimed that the Microsoft implementation did not support Java remote method invocation (RMI) or Java Native Interface (JNI) and had added platform-specific features of their own.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Sun sued in 1997, and, in 2001, won a settlement of US$20 million, as well as a court order enforcing the terms of the license from Sun.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] As a result, Microsoft no longer ships Java with Windows.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Platform-independent Java is essential to Java EE, and an even more rigorous validation is required to certify an implementation.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] This environment enables portable server-side applications.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The Java programming language requires the presence of a software platform in order for compiled programs to be executed.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Oracle supplies the Java platform for use with Java.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The Android SDK is an alternative software platform, used primarily for developing Android applications with its own GUI system.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The Java language is a key pillar in Android, an open source mobile operating system.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Although Android, built on the Linux kernel, is written largely in C, the Android SDK uses the Java language as the basis for Android applications but does not use any of its standard GUI, SE, ME or other established Java standards.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The bytecode language supported by the Android SDK is incompatible with JVM bytecode and runs on its own virtual machine, optimized for low-memory devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Depending on the Android version, the bytecode is either interpreted by the Dalvik virtual machine or compiled into native code by the Android Runtime.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Android does not provide the full Java SE standard library, although the Android SDK does include an independent implementation of a large subset of it.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] It supports Java 6 and some Java 7 features, offering an implementation compatible with the standard library (Apache Harmony).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] Under HTTP 1.0, connections should always be **closed** by the server after sending the response.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] Since at least late 1995, developers of popular products (browsers, web servers, etc.) using HTTP/1.0, started to add an unofficial extension (to the protocol) named "keep-alive" in order to allow the reuse of a connection for multiple requests/responses.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] When the server receives this request and generates a response, if it supports keep-alive then it also adds the same above header to the response.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] Following this, the connection is not dropped, but is instead kept open.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] When the client sends another request, it uses the same connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] After that the connection is closed following specified rules.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] Since 1997, the various versions of HTTP/1.1 specifications acknowledged the usage of this unofficial extension and included a few caveats regarding the interoperability between HTTP/1.0 (keep-alive) and HTTP/1.1 clients / servers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] In HTTP 1.1, all connections are considered persistent unless declared otherwise.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] The HTTP **persistent connections** do not use separate keepalive messages, they just allow multiple requests to use a single connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] However, the default connection timeout of Apache httpd 1.3 and 2.0 is as little as 15 seconds and just 5 seconds for Apache httpd 2.2 and above.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] The advantage of a short timeout is the ability to deliver multiple components of a web page quickly while not consuming resources to run multiple server processes or threads for too long.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] Keepalive makes it difficult for the client to determine where one response ends and the next response begins, particularly during pipelined HTTP operation.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] This is a serious problem when `Content-Length` cannot be used due to streaming.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] To solve this problem, HTTP 1.1 introduced a chunked transfer coding that defines a `last-chunk` bit.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] The `last-chunk` bit is set at the end of each response so that the client knows where the next response begins.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] According to RFC 7230, section 6.4, "a client ought to limit the number of simultaneous open connections that it maintains to a given server".
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] The previous version of the HTTP/1.1 specification stated specific maximum values but in the words of RFC 7230 "this was found to be impractical for many applications... instead... be conservative when opening multiple connections".
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] These guidelines are intended to improve HTTP response times and avoid congestion.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] If HTTP pipelining is correctly implemented, there is no performance benefit to be gained from additional connections, while additional connections may cause issues with congestion.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] If the client does not close the connection when all of the data it needs has been received, the resources needed to keep the connection open on the server will be unavailable for other clients.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] This affects both server's availability and the availability of resources on the server, with the degree of impact depending on the server's architecture and configuration.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] Also a race condition can occur where the client sends a request to the server at the same time that the server closes the TCP connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] A server should send a 408 Request Timeout status code to the client immediately before closing the connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] When a client receives the 408 status code, after having sent the request, it may open a new connection to the server and re-send the request.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] Not all clients will re-send the request, and many that do will only do so if the request has an idempotent HTTP method.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] All modern web browsers including Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Opera (since 4.0), and Safari use persistent connections.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] In Firefox, the number of simultaneous connections can be customized (per-server, per-proxy, total).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] Persistent connections time out after 115 seconds (1.92 minutes) of inactivity which is changeable via the configuration.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/persistent-connection] Python's `requests` library contains `requests.Session()`, which establishes a persistent HTTP connection, thereby allowing the underlying TCP connection to be reused, which can result in a significant performance increase.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS protocol aims primarily to provide security, including privacy (confidentiality), integrity, and authenticity through the use of cryptography, such as the use of certificates, between two or more communicating computer applications.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] It runs in the presentation layer and is itself composed of two layers: the TLS record and the TLS handshake protocols.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The closely-related Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is a communications protocol that provides security to datagram-based applications.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] In technical writing, references to "(D)TLS" are often seen when it applies to both versions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is a proposed Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) standard, first defined in 1999, and the current version is TLS 1.3, defined in August 2018.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS builds on the now-deprecated **SSL** (**Secure Sockets Layer**) specifications (1994, 1995, 1996) developed by Netscape Communications for adding the HTTPS protocol to their Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Client–server applications use the TLS protocol to communicate across a network in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Since applications can communicate either with or without TLS (or SSL), it is necessary for the client to request that the server set up a TLS connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] One of the main ways of achieving this is to use a different port number for TLS connections.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Port 80 is typically used for unencrypted HTTP traffic while port 443 is the common port used for encrypted HTTPS traffic.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Another mechanism is to make a protocol-specific STARTTLS request to the server to switch the connection to TLS – for example, when using some mail and news protocols.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Once the client and server have agreed to use TLS, they negotiate a stateful connection by using a handshaking procedure (see § TLS handshake).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The protocols use a handshake with an asymmetric cipher to establish not only cipher settings but also a session-specific shared key with which further communication is encrypted using a symmetric cipher.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] This concludes the handshake and begins the secured connection, which is encrypted and decrypted with the session key until the connection closes.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] If any one of the above steps fails, then the TLS handshake fails and the connection is not created.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Note that TLS 1.3 only allows key exchange algorithms providing forward secrecy.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Consequently, establishing a PreMasterSecret using the server's public and private key is only available in TLS 1.2 and below.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS and SSL do not fit neatly into any single layer of the OSI model or the TCP/IP model.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS runs "on top of some reliable transport protocol (e.g., TCP)", which would imply that it is above the transport layer.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] It serves encryption to higher layers, which is normally the function of the presentation layer.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] However, applications generally use TLS as if it were a transport layer, even though applications using TLS must actively control initiating TLS handshakes and handling of exchanged authentication certificates.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS supports many different methods for exchanging keys, encrypting data, and authenticating message integrity.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, secure configuration of TLS involves many configurable parameters, and not all choices provide all of the privacy-related properties described in the list above (see the tables below § Key exchange, § Cipher security, and § Data integrity).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Attempts have been made to subvert aspects of the communications security that TLS seeks to provide, and the protocol has been revised several times to address these security threats.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Developers of web browsers have repeatedly revised their products to defend against potential security weaknesses after these were discovered (see TLS/SSL support history of web browsers).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Datagram Transport Layer Security, abbreviated DTLS, is a related communications protocol providing security to datagram-based applications by allowing them to communicate in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping, tampering, or message forgery.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The DTLS protocol is based on the stream-oriented Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol and is intended to provide similar security guarantees.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] As the DTLS protocol datagram preserves the semantics of the underlying transport, the application does not suffer from the delays associated with stream protocols.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] However, the application has to deal with packet reordering, loss of datagram and data larger than the size of a datagram network packet.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Because DTLS uses UDP or SCTP rather than TCP, it avoids the TCP meltdown problem, when being used to create a VPN tunnel.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The original 2006 release of DTLS version 1.0 was not a standalone document.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given as a series of deltas to TLS 1.1.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Similarly the follow-up 2012 release of DTLS is a delta to TLS 1.2.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given the version number of DTLS 1.2 to match its TLS version.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Lastly, the 2022 DTLS 1.3 is a delta to TLS 1.3.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Like the two previous versions, DTLS 1.3 is intended to provide "equivalent security guarantees [to TLS 1.3] with the exception of order protection/non-replayability".
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Many VPN clients including Cisco AnyConnect & InterCloud Fabric, OpenConnect, ZScaler tunnel, F5 Networks Edge VPN Client, and Citrix Systems NetScaler use DTLS to secure UDP traffic.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] In addition all modern web browsers support DTLS-SRTP for WebRTC.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] It was intended to complement the rapidly emerging new OSI internet standards moving forward both in the U.S. government's GOSIP Profiles and in the huge ITU-ISO JTC1 internet effort internationally.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] As part of the project, researchers designed a protocol called SP4 (*security protocol* in layer 4 of the OSI system).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] This was later renamed the Transport Layer Security Protocol (TLSP) and subsequently published in 1995 as international standard ITU-T X.274|ISO/IEC 10736:1995.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the name similarity, this is distinct from today's TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] SNP was published and presented in the 1994 USENIX Summer Technical Conference.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The SNP project was funded by a grant from NSA to Professor Simon Lam at UT-Austin in 1991.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Secure Network Programming won the 2004 ACM Software System Award.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Netscape developed the original SSL protocols, and Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications from 1995 to 1998, has been described as the "father of SSL".
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL version 1.0 was never publicly released because of serious security flaws in the protocol.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Version 2.0, after being released in February 1995 was quickly found to contain a number of security and usability flaws.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] It used the same cryptographic keys for message authentication and encryption.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] It had a weak MAC construction that used the MD5 hash function with a secret prefix, making it vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] It also provided no protection for either the opening handshake or an explicit message close, both of which meant man-in-the-middle attacks could go undetected.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Moreover, SSL 2.0 assumed a single service and a fixed domain certificate, conflicting with the widely used feature of virtual hosting in Web servers, so most websites were effectively impaired from using SSL.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] These flaws necessitated the complete redesign of the protocol to SSL version 3.0.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Released in 1996, it was produced by Paul Kocher working with Netscape engineers Phil Karlton and Alan Freier, with a reference implementation by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Newer versions of SSL/TLS are based on SSL 3.0.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The 1996 draft of SSL 3.0 was published by IETF as a historical document in RFC 6101.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 2.0 was deprecated in 2011 by RFC 6176.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2014, SSL 3.0 was found to be vulnerable to the POODLE attack that affects all block ciphers in SSL; RC4, the only non-block cipher supported by SSL 3.0, is also feasibly broken as used in SSL 3.0.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 3.0 was deprecated in June 2015 by RFC 7568.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 was first defined in RFC 2246 in January 1999 as an upgrade of SSL Version 3.0, and written by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] As stated in the RFC, "the differences between this protocol and SSL 3.0 are not dramatic, but they are significant enough to preclude interoperability between TLS 1.0 and SSL 3.0".
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Tim Dierks later wrote that these changes, and the renaming from "SSL" to "TLS", were a face-saving gesture to Microsoft, "so it wouldn't look [like] the IETF was just rubberstamping Netscape's protocol".
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The PCI Council suggested that organizations migrate from TLS 1.0 to TLS 1.1 or higher before June 30, 2018.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] In October 2018, Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla jointly announced they would deprecate TLS 1.0 and 1.1 in March 2020.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 were formally deprecated in RFC 8996 in March 2021.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.1 was defined in RFC 4346 in April 2006.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS versions 1.0 and 1.1 was widely deprecated by web sites around 2020, disabling access to Firefox versions before 24 and Chromium-based browsers before 29, though third-party fixes can be applied to Netscape Navigator and older versions of Firefox to add TLS 1.2 support.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.2 was defined in RFC 5246 in August 2008.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.1 specification.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] All TLS versions were further refined in RFC 6176 in March 2011, removing their backward compatibility with SSL such that TLS sessions never negotiate the use of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) version 2.0.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] As of April 2025 there is no formal date for TLS 1.2 to be deprecated.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was defined in RFC 8446 in August 2018.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.2 specification.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Network Security Services (NSS), the cryptography library developed by Mozilla and used by its web browser Firefox, enabled TLS 1.3 by default in February 2017.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 support was subsequently added — but due to compatibility issues for a small number of users, not automatically enabled — to Firefox 52.0, which was released in March 2017.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was enabled by default in May 2018 with the release of Firefox 60.0.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Google Chrome set TLS 1.3 as the default version for a short time in 2017.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] It then removed it as the default, due to incompatible middleboxes such as Blue Coat web proxies.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The intolerance of the new version of TLS was protocol ossification; middleboxes had ossified the protocol's version parameter.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, version 1.3 mimics the wire image of version 1.2.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] This change occurred very late in the design process, only having been discovered during browser deployment.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The discovery of this intolerance also led to the prior version negotiation strategy, where the highest matching version was picked, being abandoned due to unworkable levels of ossification.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] 'Greasing' an extension point, where one protocol participant claims support for non-existent extensions to ensure that unrecognised-but-actually-existent extensions are tolerated and so to resist ossification, was originally designed for TLS, but it has since been adopted elsewhere.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] During the IETF 100 Hackathon, which took place in Singapore in 2017, the TLS Group worked on adapting open-source applications to use TLS 1.3.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS group was made up of individuals from Japan, United Kingdom, and Mauritius via the cyberstorm.mu team.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] This work was continued in the IETF 101 Hackathon in London, and the IETF 102 Hackathon in Montreal.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] wolfSSL enabled the use of TLS 1.3 as of version 3.11.1, released in May 2017.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] As the first commercial TLS 1.3 implementation, wolfSSL 3.11.1 supported Draft 18 and now supports Draft 28, the final version, as well as many older versions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] A series of blogs were published on the performance difference between TLS 1.2 and 1.3.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] In September 2018, the popular OpenSSL project released version 1.1.1 of its library, in which support for TLS 1.3 was "the headline new feature".
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS 1.3 was added to Secure Channel (schannel) for the GA releases of Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The Electronic Frontier Foundation praised TLS 1.3 and expressed concern about the variant protocol Enterprise Transport Security (ETS) that intentionally disables important security measures in TLS 1.3.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Originally called Enterprise TLS (eTLS), ETS is a published standard known as the 'ETSI TS103523-3', "Middlebox Security Protocol, Part3: Enterprise Transport Security".
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] It is intended for use entirely within proprietary networks such as banking systems.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] ETS does not support forward secrecy so as to allow third-party organizations connected to the proprietary networks to be able to use their private key to monitor network traffic for the detection of malware and to make it easier to conduct audits.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the claimed benefits, the EFF warned that the loss of forward secrecy could make it easier for data to be exposed along with saying that there are better ways to analyze traffic.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate, and indicates certain expected usages of that key.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made by the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Keystores and trust stores can be in various formats, such as .pem, .crt, .pfx, and .jks.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS typically relies on a set of trusted third-party certificate authorities to establish the authenticity of certificates.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Trust is usually anchored in a list of certificates distributed with user agent software, and can be modified by the relying party.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] According to Netcraft, who monitors active TLS certificates, the market-leading certificate authority (CA) has been Symantec since the beginning of their survey (or VeriSign before the authentication services business unit was purchased by Symantec).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] As of 2015, Symantec accounted for just under a third of all certificates and 44% of the valid certificates used by the 1 million busiest websites, as counted by Netcraft.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2017, Symantec sold its TLS/SSL business to DigiCert.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] In an updated report, it was shown that IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo are the top 3 certificate authorities in terms of market share since May 2019.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] As a consequence of choosing X.509 certificates, certificate authorities and a public key infrastructure are necessary to verify the relation between a certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] On April 11, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum approved a ballot that will require all public TLS certificate lifespans to gradually reduce to 47 days by 2029.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Before a client and server can begin to exchange information protected by TLS, they must securely exchange or agree upon an encryption key and a cipher to use when encrypting data (see § Cipher).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS_DH_anon and TLS_ECDH_anon key agreement methods do not authenticate the server or the user and hence are rarely used because those are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Only TLS_DHE and TLS_ECDHE provide forward secrecy.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Public key certificates used during exchange/agreement also vary in the size of the public/private encryption keys used during the exchange and hence the robustness of the security provided.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] In July 2013, Google announced that it would no longer use 1024-bit public keys and would switch instead to 2048-bit keys to increase the security of the TLS encryption it provides to its users because the encryption strength is directly related to the key size.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] If libraries implement fixes listed in RFC 5746, this violates the SSL 3.0 specification, which the IETF cannot change unlike TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Most current libraries implement the fix and disregard the violation that this causes.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The BEAST attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The POODLE attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] AEAD ciphers (such as GCM and CCM) can only be used in TLS 1.2 or later.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] CBC ciphers can be attacked with the Lucky Thirteen attack if the library is not written carefully to eliminate timing side channels.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The Sweet32 attack breaks block ciphers with a block size of 64 bits.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Although the key length of 3DES is 168 bits, effective security strength of 3DES is only 112 bits, which is below the recommended minimum of 128 bits.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] IDEA and DES have been removed from TLS 1.2.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] 40-bit strength cipher suites were intentionally designed with reduced key lengths to comply with since-rescinded US regulations forbidding the export of cryptographic software containing certain strong encryption algorithms (see Export of cryptography from the United States).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] These weak suites are forbidden in TLS 1.1 and later.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Use of RC4 in all versions of TLS is prohibited because RC4 attacks weaken or break RC4 used in SSL/TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] A message authentication code (MAC) is used for data integrity.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC is used for CBC mode of block ciphers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Authenticated encryption (AEAD) such as GCM and CCM mode uses AEAD-integrated MAC and does not use HMAC.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC-based PRF, or HKDF is used for TLS handshake.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] In applications design, TLS is usually implemented on top of Transport Layer protocols, encrypting all of the protocol-related data of protocols such as HTTP, FTP, SMTP, NNTP and XMPP.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Historically, TLS has been used primarily with reliable transport protocols such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] However, it has also been implemented with datagram-oriented transport protocols, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP), usage of which has been standardized independently using the term *Datagram Transport Layer Security* (*DTLS*).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] A primary use of TLS is to secure World Wide Web traffic between a website and a web browser encoded with the HTTP protocol.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] This use of TLS to secure HTTP traffic constitutes the HTTPS protocol.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] As of March 2025, the latest versions of all major web browsers support TLS 1.2 and 1.3 and have them enabled by default, with the exception of IE 11.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are disabled by default on the latest versions of all major browsers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Most SSL and TLS programming libraries are free and open-source software.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] A paper presented at the 2012 ACM conference on computer and communications security showed that many applications used some of these SSL libraries incorrectly, leading to vulnerabilities.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) can also be protected by TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] These applications use public key certificates to verify the identity of endpoints.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can also be used for tunneling an entire network stack to create a VPN, which is the case with OpenVPN and OpenConnect.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Many vendors have by now married TLS's encryption and authentication capabilities with authorization.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] There has also been substantial development since the late 1990s in creating client technology outside of Web-browsers, in order to enable support for client/server applications.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] Compared to traditional IPsec VPN technologies, TLS has some inherent advantages in firewall and NAT traversal that make it easier to administer for large remote-access populations.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is also a standard method for protecting Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) application signaling.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can be used for providing authentication and encryption of the SIP signaling associated with VoIP and other SIP-based applications.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Significant attacks against TLS/SSL are listed below.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, IETF issued an informational RFC summarizing the various known attacks against TLS/SSL.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] A vulnerability of the renegotiation procedure was discovered in August 2009 that can lead to plaintext injection attacks against SSL 3.0 and all current versions of TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] For example, it allows an attacker who can hijack an https connection to splice their own requests into the beginning of the conversation the client has with the web server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacker cannot actually decrypt the client–server communication, so it is different from a typical man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] A short-term fix is for web servers to stop allowing renegotiation, which typically will not require other changes unless client certificate authentication is used.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] To fix the vulnerability, a renegotiation indication extension was proposed for TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] It will require the client and server to include and verify information about previous handshakes in any renegotiation handshakes.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension has been implemented by several libraries.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] A protocol downgrade attack (also called a version rollback attack) tricks a web server into negotiating connections with previous versions of TLS (such as SSLv2) that have long since been abandoned as insecure.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Previous modifications to the original protocols, like **False Start** (adopted and enabled by Google Chrome) or **Snap Start**, reportedly introduced limited TLS protocol downgrade attacks or allowed modifications to the cipher suite list sent by the client to the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In doing so, an attacker might succeed in influencing the cipher suite selection in an attempt to downgrade the cipher suite negotiated to use either a weaker symmetric encryption algorithm or a weaker key exchange.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] A paper presented at an ACM conference on computer and communications security in 2012 demonstrated that the False Start extension was at risk: in certain circumstances it could allow an attacker to recover the encryption keys offline and to access the encrypted data.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Encryption downgrade attacks can force servers and clients to negotiate a connection using cryptographically weak keys.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2014, a man-in-the-middle attack called FREAK was discovered affecting the OpenSSL stack, the default Android web browser, and some Safari browsers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack involved tricking servers into negotiating a TLS connection using cryptographically weak 512 bit encryption keys.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Logjam is a security exploit discovered in May 2015 that exploits the option of using legacy "export-grade" 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups dating back to the 1990s.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] It forces susceptible servers to downgrade to cryptographically weak 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker can then deduce the keys the client and server determine using the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The DROWN attack is an exploit that attacks servers supporting contemporary SSL/TLS protocol suites by exploiting their support for the obsolete, insecure, SSLv2 protocol to leverage an attack on connections using up-to-date protocols that would otherwise be secure.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] DROWN exploits a vulnerability in the protocols used and the configuration of the server, rather than any specific implementation error.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Full details of DROWN were announced in March 2016, together with a patch for the exploit.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] At that time, more than 81,000 of the top 1 million most popular websites were among the TLS protected websites that were vulnerable to the DROWN attack.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Practical exploits had not been previously demonstrated for this vulnerability, which was originally discovered by Phillip Rogaway in 2002.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability of the attack had been fixed with TLS 1.1 in 2006, but TLS 1.1 had not seen wide adoption prior to this attack demonstration.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] RC4 as a stream cipher is immune to BEAST attack.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, RC4 was widely used as a way to mitigate BEAST attack on the server side.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] However, in 2013, researchers found more weaknesses in RC4.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Thereafter enabling RC4 on server side was no longer recommended.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Chrome and Firefox themselves are not vulnerable to BEAST attack, however, Mozilla updated their NSS libraries to mitigate BEAST-like attacks.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] NSS is used by Mozilla Firefox and Google Chrome to implement SSL.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Some web servers that have a broken implementation of the SSL specification may stop working as a result.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Microsoft released Security Bulletin MS12-006 on January 10, 2012, which fixed the BEAST vulnerability by changing the way that the Windows Secure Channel (Schannel) component transmits encrypted network packets from the server end.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Users of Internet Explorer (prior to version 11) that run on older versions of Windows (Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows Server 2008 R2) can restrict use of TLS to 1.1 or higher.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Apple mitigated the BEAST vulnerability by implementing a 1/n-1 split and turning it on by default in OS X Mavericks, released on October 22, 2013.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The authors of the BEAST attack are also the creators of the later CRIME attack, which can allow an attacker to recover the content of web cookies when data compression is used along with TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] When used to recover the content of secret authentication cookies, it allows an attacker to perform session hijacking on an authenticated web session.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The CRIME exploit against HTTP compression has not been mitigated at all, even though the authors of CRIME have warned that this vulnerability might be even more widespread than SPDY and TLS compression combined.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2013 a new instance of the CRIME attack against HTTP compression, dubbed BREACH, was announced.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] All versions of TLS and SSL are at risk from BREACH regardless of the encryption algorithm or cipher used.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a known limitation of TLS as it is susceptible to chosen-plaintext attack against the application-layer data it was meant to protect.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Earlier TLS versions were vulnerable against the padding oracle attack discovered in 2002.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] A novel variant, called the Lucky Thirteen attack, was published in 2013.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Some experts also recommended avoiding triple DES CBC.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] A fix was released in 2014 as the Encrypt-then-MAC extension to the TLS specification.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The Lucky Thirteen attack can be mitigated in TLS 1.2 by using only AES_GCM ciphers; AES_CBC remains vulnerable.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] SSL may safeguard email, VoIP, and other types of communications over insecure networks in addition to its primary use case of secure data transmission between a client and the server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] On October 14, 2014, Google researchers published a vulnerability in the design of SSL 3.0, which makes CBC mode of operation with SSL 3.0 vulnerable to a padding attack (CVE-2014-3566).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] They named this attack **POODLE** (**Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption**).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] On average, attackers only need to make 256 SSL 3.0 requests to reveal one byte of encrypted messages.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, the man-in-the-middle can first conduct a version rollback attack and then exploit this vulnerability.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] On December 8, 2014, a variant of POODLE was announced that impacts TLS implementations that do not properly enforce padding byte requirements.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Despite the existence of attacks on RC4 that broke its security, cipher suites in SSL and TLS that were based on RC4 were still considered secure prior to 2013 based on the way in which they were used in SSL and TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2011, the RC4 suite was actually recommended as a workaround for the BEAST attack.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] New forms of attack disclosed in March 2013 conclusively demonstrated the feasibility of breaking RC4 in TLS, suggesting it was not a good workaround for BEAST.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack scenario was proposed by AlFardan, Bernstein, Paterson, Poettering and Schuldt that used newly discovered statistical biases in the RC4 key table to recover parts of the plaintext with a large number of TLS encryptions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack on RC4 in TLS and SSL that requires 13 × 220 encryptions to break RC4 was unveiled on 8 July 2013 and later described as "feasible" in the accompanying presentation at a USENIX Security Symposium in August 2013.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In July 2015, subsequent improvements in the attack make it increasingly practical to defeat the security of RC4-encrypted TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] As many modern browsers have been designed to defeat BEAST attacks (except Safari for Mac OS X 10.7 or earlier, for iOS 6 or earlier, and for Windows; see § Web browsers), RC4 is no longer a good choice for TLS 1.0.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The CBC ciphers which were affected by the BEAST attack in the past have become a more popular choice for protection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Mozilla and Microsoft recommend disabling RC4 where possible.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, the use of RC4 cipher suites was officially prohibited in all versions of TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] On September 1, 2015, Microsoft, Google, and Mozilla announced that RC4 cipher suites would be disabled by default in their browsers (Microsoft Edge [Legacy], Internet Explorer 11 on Windows 7/8.1/10, Firefox, and Chrome) in early 2016.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] A TLS (logout) truncation attack blocks a victim's account logout requests so that the user unknowingly remains logged into a web service.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] When the request to sign out is sent, the attacker injects an unencrypted TCP FIN message (no more data from sender) to close the connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The server therefore does not receive the logout request and is unaware of the abnormal termination.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack does not rely on installing malware on the victim's computer; attackers need only place themselves between the victim and the web server (e.g., by setting up a rogue wireless hotspot).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This vulnerability also requires access to the victim's computer.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Another possibility is when using FTP the data connection can have a false FIN in the data stream, and if the protocol rules for exchanging close_notify alerts is not adhered to a file can be truncated.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2013 two researchers from Royal Holloway, University of London discovered a timing attack which allowed them to recover (parts of the) plaintext from a DTLS connection using the OpenSSL or GnuTLS implementation of DTLS when Cipher Block Chaining mode encryption was used.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, discovered in mid-2016, exploits weaknesses in the Web Proxy Autodiscovery Protocol (WPAD) to expose the URL that a web user is attempting to reach via a TLS-enabled web link.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Disclosure of a URL can violate a user's privacy, not only because of the website accessed, but also because URLs are sometimes used to authenticate users.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Document sharing services, such as those offered by Google and Dropbox, also work by sending a user a security token that is included in the URL.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker who obtains such URLs may be able to gain full access to a victim's account or data.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The exploit works against almost all browsers and operating systems.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The Sweet32 attack breaks all 64-bit block ciphers used in CBC mode as used in TLS by exploiting a birthday attack and either a man-in-the-middle attack or injection of a malicious JavaScript into a web page.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The purpose of the man-in-the-middle attack or the JavaScript injection is to allow the attacker to capture enough traffic to mount a birthday attack.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug is a serious vulnerability specific to the implementation of SSL/TLS in the popular OpenSSL cryptographic software library, affecting versions 1.0.1 to 1.0.1f.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This weakness, reported in April 2014, allows attackers to extract private keys from servers that should normally be protected.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug allows anyone on the Internet to read the memory of the systems protected by the vulnerable versions of the OpenSSL software.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This compromises the secret private keys associated with the public certificates used to identify the service providers and to encrypt the traffic, the names and passwords of the users and the actual content.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This allows attackers to eavesdrop on communications, extract data directly from the services and users and to impersonate services and users.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability is caused by a buffer over-read bug in the OpenSSL software, rather than a defect in the SSL or TLS protocol specification.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In September 2014, a variant of Daniel Bleichenbacher's PKCS#1 v1.5 RSA Signature Forgery vulnerability was announced by Intel Security Advanced Threat Research.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, dubbed BERserk, is a result of incomplete ASN.1 length decoding of public key signatures in some SSL implementations, and allows a man-in-the-middle attack by forging a public key signature.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, after media reported the hidden pre-installation of superfish adware on some Lenovo notebooks, a researcher found a trusted root certificate on affected Lenovo machines to be insecure, as the keys could easily be accessed using the company name, Komodia, as a passphrase.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The Komodia library was designed to intercept client-side TLS/SSL traffic for parental control and surveillance, but it was also used in numerous adware programs, including Superfish, that were often surreptitiously installed unbeknownst to the computer user.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In turn, these potentially unwanted programs installed the corrupt root certificate, allowing attackers to completely control web traffic and confirm false websites as authentic.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In May 2016, it was reported that dozens of Danish HTTPS-protected websites belonging to Visa Inc. were vulnerable to attacks allowing hackers to inject malicious code and forged content into the browsers of visitors.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacks worked because the TLS implementation used on the affected servers incorrectly reused random numbers (nonces) that are intended to be used only once, ensuring that each TLS handshake is unique.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2017, an implementation error caused by a single mistyped character in code used to parse HTML created a buffer overflow error on Cloudflare servers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Similar in its effects to the Heartbleed bug discovered in 2014, this overflow error, widely known as Cloudbleed, allowed unauthorized third parties to read data in the memory of programs running on the servers—data that should otherwise have been protected by TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] As of June 2025, the Trustworthy Internet Movement estimated the ratio of websites that are vulnerable to TLS attacks.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Forward secrecy is a property of cryptographic systems which ensures that a session key derived from a set of public and private keys will not be compromised if one of the private keys is compromised in the future.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] An implementation of TLS can provide forward secrecy by requiring the use of ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to establish session keys, and some notable TLS implementations do so exclusively: e.g., Gmail and other Google HTTPS services that use OpenSSL.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] However, many clients and servers supporting TLS (including browsers and web servers) are not configured to implement such restrictions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In practice, unless a web service uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange to implement forward secrecy, all of the encrypted web traffic to and from that service can be decrypted by a third party if it obtains the server's master (private) key; e.g., by means of a court order.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Even where Diffie–Hellman key exchange is implemented, server-side session management mechanisms can impact forward secrecy.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of TLS session tickets (a TLS extension) causes the session to be protected by AES128-CBC-SHA256 regardless of any other negotiated TLS parameters, including forward secrecy ciphersuites, and the long-lived TLS session ticket keys defeat the attempt to implement forward secrecy.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Stanford University research in 2014 also found that of 473,802 TLS servers surveyed, 82.9% of the servers deploying ephemeral Diffie–Hellman (DHE) key exchange to support forward secrecy were using weak Diffie–Hellman parameters.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] These weak parameter choices could potentially compromise the effectiveness of the forward secrecy that the servers sought to provide.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Since late 2011, Google has provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, along with Google Docs and encrypted search, among other services.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Since November 2013, Twitter has provided forward secrecy with TLS to users of its service.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] As of August 2019, about 80% of TLS-enabled websites are configured to use cipher suites that provide forward secrecy to most web browsers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS interception (or HTTPS interception if applied particularly to that protocol) is the practice of intercepting an encrypted data stream in order to decrypt it, read and possibly manipulate it, and then re-encrypt it and send the data on its way again.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This is done by way of a "transparent proxy": the interception software terminates the incoming TLS connection, inspects the HTTP plaintext, and then creates a new TLS connection to the destination.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS/HTTPS interception is used as an information security measure by network operators in order to be able to scan for and protect against the intrusion of malicious content into the network, such as computer viruses and other malware.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Such content could otherwise not be detected as long as it is protected by encryption, which is increasingly the case as a result of the routine use of HTTPS and other secure protocols.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] A significant drawback of TLS/HTTPS interception is that it introduces new security risks of its own.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] One notable limitation is that it provides a point where network traffic is available unencrypted thus giving attackers an incentive to attack this point in particular in order to gain access to otherwise secure content.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The interception also allows the network operator, or persons who gain access to its interception system, to perform man-in-the-middle attacks against network users.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] A 2017 study found that "HTTPS interception has become startlingly widespread, and that interception products as a class have a dramatically negative impact on connection security".
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS protocol exchanges *records*, which encapsulate the data to be exchanged in a specific format (see below).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record can be compressed, padded, appended with a message authentication code (MAC), or encrypted, all depending on the state of the connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record has a *content type* field that designates the type of data encapsulated, a length field and a TLS version field.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The data encapsulated may be control or procedural messages of the TLS itself, or simply the application data needed to be transferred by TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The specifications (cipher suite, keys etc.) required to exchange application data by TLS, are agreed upon in the "TLS handshake" between the client requesting the data and the server responding to requests.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The protocol therefore defines both the structure of payloads transferred in TLS and the procedure to establish and monitor the transfer.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] When the connection starts, the record encapsulates a "control" protocol – the handshake messaging protocol (*content type* 22).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This protocol is used to exchange all the information required by both sides for the exchange of the actual application data by TLS.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines the format of messages and the order of their exchange.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] These may vary according to the demands of the client and server – i.e., there are several possible procedures to set up the connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This initial exchange results in a successful TLS connection (both parties ready to transfer application data with TLS) or an alert message (as specified below).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Application phase: at this point, the "handshake" is complete and the application protocol is enabled, with content type of 23.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be authenticated and optionally encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the content type will return 25 and the client will not authenticate.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The following *full* example shows a client being authenticated (in addition to the server as in the example above; see mutual authentication) via TLS using certificates exchanged between both peers.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The client now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the server, "Everything I tell you from now on will be authenticated (and encrypted if encryption was negotiated).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] "The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Public key operations (e.g., RSA) are relatively expensive in terms of computational power.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS provides a secure shortcut in the handshake mechanism to avoid these operations: resumed sessions.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Resumed sessions are implemented using session IDs or session tickets.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Apart from the performance benefit, resumed sessions can also be used for single sign-on, as it guarantees that both the original session and any resumed session originate from the same client.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This is of particular importance for the FTP over TLS/SSL protocol, which would otherwise suffer from a man-in-the-middle attack in which an attacker could intercept the contents of the secondary data connections.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS 1.3 handshake was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] To start the handshake, the client guesses which key exchange algorithm will be selected by the server and sends a **ClientHello** message to the server containing a list of supported ciphers (in order of the client's preference) and public keys for some or all of its key exchange guesses.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] If the client successfully guesses the key exchange algorithm, 1 round trip is eliminated from the handshake.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] After receiving the **ClientHello**, the server selects a cipher and sends back a **ServerHello** with its own public key, followed by server **Certificate** and **Finished** messages.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] After the client receives the server's finished message, it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In an ordinary *full* handshake, the server sends a *session id* as part of the **ServerHello** message.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The client associates this *session id* with the server's IP address and TCP port, so that when the client connects again to that server, it can use the *session id* to shortcut the handshake.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In the server, the *session id* maps to the cryptographic parameters previously negotiated, specifically the "master secret".
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Both sides must have the same "master secret" or the resumed handshake will fail (this prevents an eavesdropper from using a *session id*).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The random data in the **ClientHello** and **ServerHello** messages virtually guarantee that the generated connection keys will be different from in the previous connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In the RFCs, this type of handshake is called an *abbreviated* handshake.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] It is also described in the literature as a *restart* handshake.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The server now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the client, "Everything I tell you from now on will be encrypted." The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Instead of session IDs, TLS can also be extended via use of session tickets.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines a way to resume a TLS session without requiring that session-specific state is stored at the TLS server.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] When using session tickets, the TLS server stores its session-specific state in a session ticket and sends the session ticket to the TLS client for storing.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The client resumes a TLS session by sending the session ticket to the server, and the server resumes the TLS session according to the session-specific state in the ticket.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The session ticket is encrypted and authenticated by the server, and the server verifies its validity before using its contents.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] One particular weakness of this method with OpenSSL is that it always limits encryption and authentication security of the transmitted TLS session ticket to `AES128-CBC-SHA256`, no matter what other TLS parameters were negotiated for the actual TLS session.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the state information (the TLS session ticket) is not as well protected as the TLS session itself.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This is the general format of all TLS records.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the Record Layer Protocol Type contained in this record.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the major and minor version of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 for the contained message.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] and application must send supported versions in an extra message extension block.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] One or more messages identified by the Protocol field.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that this field may be encrypted depending on the state of the connection.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] field, with additional key material included.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Most messages exchanged during the setup of the TLS session are based on this record, unless an error or warning occurs and needs to be signaled by an Alert protocol record (see below), or the encryption mode of the session is modified by another record (see **ChangeCipherSpec** protocol below).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the handshake message type.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a 3-byte field indicating the length of the handshake data, not including the header.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that multiple handshake messages may be combined within one record.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This record should normally not be sent during normal handshaking or application exchanges.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] However, this message can be sent at any time during the handshake and up to the closure of the session.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] If this is used to signal a fatal error, the session will be closed immediately after sending this record, so this record is used to give a reason for this closure.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] If the alert level is flagged as a warning, the remote can decide to close the session if it decides that the session is not reliable enough for its needs (before doing so, the remote may also send its own signal).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 2.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the level of alert.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] If the level is fatal, the sender should close the session immediately.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the recipient may decide to terminate the session itself, by sending its own fatal alert and closing the session itself immediately after sending it.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of Alert records is optional, however if it is missing before the session closure, the session may be resumed automatically (with its handshakes).
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Alert type (with a simple warning level) to prevent such automatic resume of a new session.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies which type of alert is being sent.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 1.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the CCS Protocol type.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] The last byte contains the padding length.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] From the application protocol point of view, TLS belongs to a lower layer, although the TCP/IP model is too coarse to show it.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the TLS handshake is usually (except in the STARTTLS case) performed before the application protocol can start.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] In the name-based virtual server feature being provided by the application layer, all co-hosted virtual servers share the same certificate because the server has to select and send a certificate immediately after the ClientHello message.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a big problem in hosting environments because it means either sharing the same certificate among all customers or using a different IP address for each of them.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] To provide the server name, Transport Layer Security (TLS) Extensions allow clients to include a Server Name Indication extension (SNI) in the extended ClientHello message.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension hints to the server immediately which name the client wishes to connect to, so the server can select the appropriate certificate to send to the clients.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] There is also a method to implement name-based virtual hosting by upgrading HTTP to TLS via an HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] Normally this is to securely implement HTTP over TLS within the main "http" URI scheme instead of the commonly used "https" scheme.
[src:okhttp-java-lib/transport-layer-security-p02] This would avoid forking the URI space and reduces the number of used ports, however, few implementations currently support this.
